Question: My spouse earns income from freelance consulting and also receives a
  pension. How do I assess whether her total income falls under the
  threshold for me to remain entitled to the household allowance?
Example answer: The household allowance is payable only where the gross annual income
  of the member of staff's spouse or recognised partner does not
  exceed EUR 71,764. For this purpose, "gross annual income" is
  defined as income originating in the calendar year preceding that in
  respect of which eligibility is assessed, from employment or self-
  employment, from income replacement (e.g. maternity allowance,
  parental allowance, social security benefits and unemployment
  allowance, but not payments representing reimbursement of expenses),
  or from a pension, before tax and before the deduction of social
  security contributions; investment income and income from capital
  gains are not considered. Both the freelance consulting income and
  the pension would therefore count toward the threshold. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 9; ECB Staff Rules, page 63)
Predicted answer: Here's how to assess it for your case:  - Identify gross annual income
  of your spouse for the calendar year before eligibility: add
  together income from freelance consulting (self-employment) and the
  pension. Do not include investment income or capital gains. Include
  any other applicable earnings from employment or self-employment or
  pension as defined by the rule. - Compare the total to EUR 71,764
  (the threshold for the household allowance).   - If the total is ≤
  EUR 71,764: you remain entitled to the household allowance (subject
  to the rule for two staff members: if both spouses are ECB staff and
  both are under the limit, the allowance goes to the partner with the
  higher salary).   - If the total is > EUR 71,764: you are not
  entitled to the household allowance. - Provide evidence of income as
  required (e.g., latest tax declaration and salary statements or
  other ECB-acceptable documents).  Example: - Freelance consulting:
  €40,000 - Pension: €25,000 - Total gross annual income: €65,000 → ≤
  €71,764 → eligible (if you’re the head of household; if both are
  staff and both under the limit, the higher-salary partner would
  receive the allowance). - Freelance consulting: €60,000 - Pension:
  €25,000 - Total: €85,000 → > €71,764 → not eligible.
